xyz.acygn.mokapot.util

Class DataByteBuffer

  • java.lang.Object
    • xyz.acygn.mokapot.util.DataByteBuffer
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DataInput, DataOutput
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ObjectDescription

    public class DataByteBuffer
extends Object
implements DataInput, DataOutput
    A ByteBuffer wrapped to implement (most of) the DataInput and DataOutput interfaces. The buffer can be written once, and then read any number of times, with resetForRead() called in between the write and read, and in between each read. The buffer's maximum length must be specified in advance; its actual length will become fixed only after writing is complete (and be equal to the number of bytes written).
    Author:
    Alex Smith

      • resetForRead

        public void resetForRead()
        Makes this buffer readable and read-only, and resets the read pointer. Used once writing to the buffer is complete, or once reading the buffer is complete (to allow it to be read again).

      • getWrittenLength

        public int getWrittenLength()
        Returns the number of bytes that have been written into this buffer. That is, its maximum length if it's been made read-only, or the number of bytes written so far if it's still writable.
        Returns:
        The number of bytes that have been written into the buffer.

      • isRewound

        public boolean isRewound()
        Checks to see whether this buffer is rewound. That is, that the buffer has been placed into read-only mode, and the read cursor is currently at the start of its data (indicating that none of it was read since the previous reset).
        Returns:
        true if and only if the buffer is rewound

      • isReadOnly

        public boolean isReadOnly()
        Checks to see whether this buffer is in read-only mode.
        Returns:
        true if the buffer is currently read-only.

      • toString

        public String toString()
        Produces a string representation of the buffer. This contains its contents in a human-readable form, and an indication of whether it's still writable or whether it's now read-only.

        The string representation is optimised for a mix of binary data and length-prefixed strings; in particular, sequences 3 or more bytes long that appear to be ASCII will be output as strings rather than in hexadecimal, and ASCII characters immediately before a string will not be included as part of the string if they appear to be part of a length prefix for that string.

        Overrides:
        toString in class Object
        Returns:
        A string representation of the buffer.
